  <introduction permid="aMa">
    <p permid="HhE">
      In this section,
      we will explore perimeter and area formulas for basic geometric shapes.
    </p>

    <figure permid="noN">
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtube="ZASBmoylCPc"/>
    </figure>
  </introduction>

  <section permid="Bzw">
    <title>Rectangle and Square</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-rectangle-square" permid="OqE">
      <caption>Rectangle and Square</caption>
      <image width="47%" permid="ded">
        <description>a 2x3 cm rectangle on the left and a 2x2 cm square on the right</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) rectangle (3,2);
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (4,0) rectangle (6,2);
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-1,-1) grid (7,3);
                        \node at (1.5,0) [below] {length=$3$ cm};
                        \node at (0,1) [left] {width=$2$ cm};
                        \node at (5,0) [below] {length=$2$ cm};
                        \node at (6,1) [right] {length=$2$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="mju">
      The rectangle on the left has a pair of lengths
      (top and bottom)
      and a pair of widths
      (left and right).
      The square on the right simply has four side lengths of equal size.
      A square can be considered a special rectangle whose length and width have the same size.
    </p>

    <p permid="SqD">
      <term>Perimeter</term>
          <idx><h>perimeter</h></idx>
      is the distance around a two-dimensional shape.
      To calculate perimeter, start from a point on the shape
      (usually a corner),
      travel around the shape, and calculate the sum of the distance traveled.
    </p>

    <p permid="yxM">
      For the rectangle in the figure,
      if we travel around it, the total distance would be:
      <md permid="XKq">
        <mrow>\text{rectangle perimeter}\amp=3\text{ cm}+2\text{ cm}+3\text{ cm}+2\text{ cm}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=10\text{ cm}</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p permid="eEV">
      Since a rectangle has two pairs of equal sides,
      we could have calculated the perimeter this way:
      <md permid="DRz">
        <mrow>\text{rectangle perimeter}\amp=2(3\text{ cm}+2\text{ cm})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=2(5\text{ cm})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=10\text{ cm}</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p permid="KMe">
      It's even easier to calculate the square's perimeter:
      <md permid="jYI">
        <mrow>\text{square perimeter}\amp=4(2\text{ cm})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=8\text{ cm}</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p permid="qTn">
      Let's summarize the perimeter formulas of rectangle and square:
      <dl permid="ZGH">
        <li permid="PhC">
          <title>Rectangle</title>
              <idx><h>perimeter</h><h>rectangle</h></idx>

          <p permid="zYE">
            <m>P=2(\ell+w)</m>, where <m>P</m> is the rectangle's perimeter,
            <m>\ell</m> is its length, and <m>w</m> is its width.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="voL">
          <title>Square</title>
              <idx><h>perimeter</h><h>square</h></idx>

          <p permid="gfN">
            <m>P=4\ell</m>,
            where <m>P</m> is the square's perimeter and <m>\ell</m> is its length.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </p>

    <p permid="Xaw">
      <term>Area</term>
          <idx><h>area</h></idx>
      of a two-dimensional shape is the number of unit squares that can be contained within it
      (possible after morphing them into non-square shapes).
      A unit square is a square with a side length of <m>1</m> unit.
      In <xref ref="figure-rectangle-square">Figure</xref>,
      the rectangle has <m>6</m> unit squares in it,
      so its area is <m>6</m> square centimeters;
      the square has <m>4</m> unit square in it,
      so its area is <m>4</m> square centimeters.
    </p>

    <p permid="DhF">
      To calculate the area of a rectangle,
      we usually use multiplication.
      The rectangle in <xref ref="figure-rectangle-square">Figure</xref>
      has two rows of <m>3</m> unit squares,
      so its area is <m>3\text{ cm}\cdot2\text{ cm}=6\text{ cm}^2</m>.
      In general, the area formula of rectangles and squares are:
      <dl permid="FNQ">
        <li permid="bvU">
          <title>Rectangle</title>
              <idx><h>area</h><h>rectangle</h></idx>

          <p permid="MmW">
            <m>A=\ell w</m>, where <m>A</m> is the rectangle's area,
            <m>\ell</m> is its length, and <m>w</m> is its width.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="HDd">
          <title>Square</title>
              <idx><h>area</h><h>square</h></idx>

          <p permid="suf">
            <m>A=\ell^2</m>,
            where <m>A</m> is the square's area and <m>\ell</m> is its length.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </p>

    <p permid="joO">
      Note that just as <m>3\cdot3=3^2</m>,
      we can treat units in the same way:
      <m>\text{cm}\cdot\text{cm}=\text{cm}^2</m>.
      The area unit reads "square centimeters," which is different from the length unit <m>\text{cm}</m>.
      In application problems,
      you are encouraged to include units in calculations.
    </p>

    <exercise permid="GTj">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Geometry/RectanglePerimeterArea10.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="hGF">
    <title>Parallelogram</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-parallelogram" permid="uxN">
      <caption>Parallelogram</caption>
      <image width="60%" permid="Jlm">
        <description>a parallelogram slanted to the right;the base is 3cm, the width is 1.7 cm; the height perpendicular to the base is 2 cm</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (4,2) -- (1,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-1,-1) grid (5,3);
                        \node at (1.5,0) [below] {base=$3$ cm};
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (1,2) -- (1,0);
                        \draw [red] (1,0.2) -- (1.2,0.2) -- (1.2,0);
                        \node at (0.5,1) [left] {width=$1.7$ cm};
                        \node at (1,1) [right, red] {height=$2$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="PvX">
      The shape in <xref ref="figure-parallelogram">Figure</xref>
      is called a <term>parallelogram</term>.
          <idx><h>parallelogram</h></idx>
      It is a quadrilateral (<m>4</m>-sided polygon) with two pairs of parallel sides,
      and each side has the same dimension as its opposite side.
      Note that any rectangle is a special parallelogram with <m>4</m> right angles.
    </p>

    <p permid="vDg">
      We can easily calculate a parallelogram's perimeter:
      <me permid="QfR">
        \text{parallelogram perimeter}=2(3\text{ cm}+1.7\text{ cm})=9.4\text{ cm}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p permid="bKp">
      To calculate a parallelogram's area,
      let's look at this figure:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-parallelogram-turns-into-rectangle" permid="aEW">
      <caption>Parallelogram's Area</caption>
      <image width="60%" permid="psv">
        <description>A triangle is drawn around the slanted part on the right side of the parallelogram;this area is moved to the left side of the figure which makes a rectangle</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,2) -- (0,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-1,-1) grid (5,3);
                        \draw [red,dashed,thick] (0,0) -- (0,2) -- (1,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [red,dashed,thick] (3,0) -- (3,2) -- (4,2) -- (3,0);
                        \draw [red,->] (3.5,2.2) to [out=150,in=30] (0.5,2.2);
                        \node at (1.5,0) [below] {base=$3$ cm};
                        \node at (0,1) [left] {height=$2$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="HRy">
      Once we move the right triangle from the right side to the left side,
      a parallelogram can be turned into a rectangle with the same area.
      Thus, a parallelogram's area can be calculated by a rectangle's area formula:
      <me permid="wna">
        \text{Parallelogram Area}=bh
      </me>
      where <m>b</m> stands for the parallelogram's base and <m>h</m> for its height.
          <idx><h>area</h><h>parallelogram</h></idx>
    </p>

    <exercise permid="nas">
      <webwork seed="2">
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
              Context("Numeric");
              $refreshCachedImages = 1;

              $unit = "ft";

              $xmin = 0;         #The viewing window
              $xmax = 20;
              $ymin = 0;
              $ymax = 20;

              do {
                 $base = random(10,15,1);
                 $height = random(5,9,1);
                 $side = random($height+1,$height+5,1);
                 $extension = sqrt($side**2-$height**2);
                 $newBase = $base+$extension;
              } until ($newBase&lt;18);

              $baseU = NumberWithUnits("$base $unit");
              $heightU = NumberWithUnits("$height $unit");
              $sideU = NumberWithUnits("$side $unit");

              @x = (($xmax-$newBase)/2,($xmax+$newBase)/2);
              @y = (($ymax-$height)/2,($ymax+$height)/2);

              $cornersize = min(($x[1]-$x[0]),($y[1]-$y[0]))/10;

              $picture = init_graph($xmin,$ymin,$xmax,$ymax,
                    pixels=>[400,400]);

              $picture->lb( new Label(($x[0]+$x[1]-$extension)/2, $y[0]-0.5,"$baseU",'black','center','middle'));
              $picture->lb( new Label($x[0]+$extension+0.5,($y[0]+$y[1])/2,"$heightU",'black','left','middle'));
              $picture->lb( new Label($x[0]+$extension/2-0.5,($y[0]+$y[1])/2,"$sideU",'black','right','middle'));

              $picture->new_color("lightblue", 200,200,255); # RGB
              $picture->new_color("darkblue",  100,100,255);

              $picture->moveTo($x[0],$y[0]);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1]-$extension,$y[0], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1],$y[1], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0]+$extension,$y[1], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0],$y[0], darkblue,3);

              $picture->moveTo($x[0]+$extension,$y[1]);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0]+$extension,$y[0], black,1,dashed);

              $picture->moveTo($x[0]+$extension,$y[0]+$cornersize);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0]+$extension+$cornersize,$y[0]+$cornersize, darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0]+$extension+$cornersize,$y[0], darkblue,3);

              $alt = "a parallelogram with a base of $baseU, a height of $heightU, and a side length of $sideU";

              $perimeter = 2*($base+$side);
              $area = $base*$height;
              $ansP = NumberWithUnits("$perimeter $unit");
              $ansA = NumberWithUnits("$area $unit^2");
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="fKo">
              Find the perimeter and area of the parallelogram.
            </p>

            <sidebyside widths="40%" permid="OxI">

              <image pg-name="$picture" permid="Laz">
                <description><var name="$alt" /></description>
              </image>

            </sidebyside>

            <p permid="LRx">
              Its perimeter is <var name="$ansP" width="8" /> and its area is <var name="$ansA" width="8" />.
            </p>

            <p permid="rYG">
              (Use <m>\text{ft}</m> for <var name="$unit" /> and
              <m>\text{ft}^2</m> for square <var name="$unit" />.)
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="QmV">
            <p permid="hVa">
              A parallelogram's opposite sides are always congruent,
              so we can calculate its perimeter by:
              <md permid="cuj">
                <mrow>\text{parallelogram perimeter}\amp=2(<var name="$baseU" />+<var name="$sideU" />)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= <var name="$ansP" /></mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

            <p permid="Ocj">
              A parallelogram's area can be calculated by this formula:
              <md permid="IBs">
                <mrow>\text{parallelogram area}\amp= \text{base} \cdot \text{height}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= <var name="$baseU" /> \cdot <var name="$heightU" /></mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = <var name="$ansA" /></mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="NNO">
    <title>Triangle</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-triangles" permid="GMf">
      <caption>Triangles</caption>
      <image width="100%" permid="VzE">
        <description>three triangles are shown from left to right;an acute triangle, a right triangle and an obtuse triangle;the height of the obtuse triangle is shown outside the triangle perpendicular to the base</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,0);
                        \node at (1.5,0) [below] {base=$3$ cm};
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (2,2) -- (2,0);
                        \draw [red] (2,0.2) -- (1.8,0.2) -- (1.8,0);
                        \node at (2,1) [right, red] {height=$2$ cm};

                        \fill[blue!20!white] (4,0) -- (7,0) -- (7,2) -- (4,0);
                        \node at (5.5,0) [below] {base=$3$ cm};
                        \draw [red] (7,0.2) -- (6.8,0.2) -- (6.8,0);
                        \node at (7,1) [right, red] {height=$2$ cm};

                        \fill[blue!20!white] (8,0) -- (11,0) -- (12,2) -- (8,0);
                        \node at (9.5,0) [below] {base=$3$ cm};
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (12,2) -- (12,0);
                        \draw [red] (12,0.2) -- (11.8,0.2) -- (11.8,0);
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (11,0) -- (12,0);
                        \node at (12,1) [right, red] {height=$2$ cm};

                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-1,-1) grid (13,3);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="nYH">
      In <xref ref="figure-triangles">Figure</xref>,
      there are <m>3</m> triangles.
      From left to right, there is an acute triangle,
      a right triangle and an obtuse triangle.
      Notice how to draw a height for an obtuse triangle.
    </p>

    <p permid="UfQ">
      The perimeter of a triangle is easy to calculate<mdash/>simply add up the length of its <m>3</m> sides.
    </p>

    <p permid="AmZ">
      To derive a triangle's area formula,
      let's look at the following figure:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-triangle-area" permid="mTo">
      <caption>Triangle's Area</caption>
      <image width="100%" permid="BGN">
        <description>the same three triangles are shown, and each is reflected across one of the sides so that its area is doubled; The doubled shape forms a paralellogram or a rectangle; the area of the triangle is half of the paralellogram or rectangle</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (0,0) -- (-1,2) -- (2,2);

                        \fill[blue!20!white] (4,0) -- (7,0) -- (7,2) -- (4,0);
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (4,0) -- (4,2) -- (7,2);

                        \fill[blue!20!white] (8,0) -- (11,0) -- (12,2) -- (8,0);
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (8,0) -- (9,2) -- (12,2);

                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-2,-1) grid (13,3);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="gui">
      If we reflect
      (or flip)
      a triangle by one of its sides,
      we will get a parallelogram or rectangle whose area is twice the triangle's area.
      In other words,
      a triangle's area is half the area of a parallelogram with the same base and height.
      Since a parallelogram's area formula is "base times height", we have:
      <me permid="oIB">
        \text{Triangle Area}=\frac{1}{2}bh
      </me>
      where <m>b</m> stands for a triangle's base and <m>h</m> for its height.
    </p>

    <exercise permid="ThB">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Geometry/TrianglePerimeterArea30.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="tUX">
    <title>Trapezoid</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-trapezoid" permid="Tax">
      <caption>Trapezoid</caption>
      <image width="60%" permid="hNW">
        <description>a trapezoid with a lower base of 5 cm, an upper base of 2 cm and a height of 2 cm</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (4,2) -- (2,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-1,-1) grid (6,3);
                        \node at (2.5,0) [below] {base1=$5$ cm};
                        \node at (3,2) [above] {base2=$2$ cm};
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (4,2) -- (4,0);
                        \draw [red] (4,0.2) -- (4.2,0.2) -- (4.2,0);
                        \node at (4,1) [left, red] {height=$2$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="MBr">
      A <term>trapezoid</term>
          <idx><h>trapezoid</h></idx>
      is a quadrilateral (<m>4</m>-sided polygon) with one and only one pair of parallel bases with different dimensions.
    </p>

    <p permid="sIA">
      We will use the following figure to derive a trapezoid's area formula:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-trapezoid-area" permid="zhG">
      <caption>Trapezoid's Area</caption>
      <image width="80%" permid="NVf">
        <description>the same trapezoid is shown, with an identical trapezoid upside down next to it;this forms a parallelogram with a length of base1 + base2</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \fill[blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (4,2) -- (2,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (0,0) -- (-2,0) -- (-3,2) -- (2,2);
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-4,-1) grid (6,3);
                        \node at (2.5,0) [below] {base1=$5$ cm};
                        \node at (3,2) [above] {base2=$2$ cm};
                        \node at (-1,0) [below] {base2=$2$ cm};
                        \node at (-0.5,2) [above] {base1=$5$ cm};
                        \draw [dashed,red,thick] (4,2) -- (4,0);
                        \draw [red] (4,0.2) -- (4.2,0.2) -- (4.2,0);
                        \node at (4,1) [left, red] {height=$2$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="YPJ">
      We can see two copies of the same trapezoid can form a parallelogram with the same height.
      The parallelogram's base is the sum of the trapezoid's two bases.
      Since a parallelogram's area formula is "base times height", we have:
      <me permid="UPK">
        \text{Trapezoid Area}=\frac{1}{2}(b_1+b_2)h
      </me>
          <idx><h>area</h><h>trapezoid</h></idx>
      where <m>b_1</m> and <m>b_2</m> stand for a trapezoid's two bases,
      and <m>h</m> for its height.
    </p>

    <exercise permid="zoK">
      <webwork seed="2">
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
              Context("Numeric");
              $refreshCachedImages = 1;

              $unit = "cm";

              $base1 = random(10,18,1);
              $base2 = random(5,$base1-1,1);
              $height = random(5,15,1);
              $x1 = random(1,$base1-$base2,1);

              $xmin = 0;         #The viewing window
              $xmax = $base1*1.2;
              $ymin = 0;
              $ymax = $xmax*$height/$base1;

              $base1U = NumberWithUnits("$base1 $unit");
              $base2U = NumberWithUnits("$base2 $unit");
              $heightU = NumberWithUnits("$height $unit");

              @x = (($xmax-$base1)/2,($xmax-$base1)/2+$x1,($xmax-$base1)/2+$base2,($xmax+$base1)/2);
              @y = (($ymax-$height)/2,($ymax+$height)/2);

              $cornersize = min(($x[1]-$x[0]),($y[1]-$y[0]))/5;

              $picture = init_graph($xmin,$ymin,$xmax,$ymax,
                    pixels=>[240,240*$height/$base1]);

              $picture->lb( new Label(($x[0]+$x[3])/2, $y[0]-0.5,"$base1U",'black','center','middle'));
              $picture->lb( new Label(($x[1]+$x[2])/2, $y[1]+0.5,"$base2U",'black','center','middle'));
              $picture->lb( new Label($x[1]+0.5,($y[0]+$y[1])/2,"$heightU",'black','left','middle'));

              $picture->new_color("lightblue", 200,200,255); # RGB
              $picture->new_color("darkblue",  100,100,255);

              $picture->moveTo($x[0],$y[0]);
              $picture->lineTo($x[3],$y[0], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[2],$y[1], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1],$y[1], darkblue,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[0],$y[0], darkblue,3);

              $picture->moveTo($x[1],$y[1]);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1],$y[0], black,1,dashed);

              $picture->moveTo($x[1],$y[0]+$cornersize);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1]+$cornersize,$y[0]+$cornersize, black,3);
              $picture->lineTo($x[1]+$cornersize,$y[0], black,3);

              $alt = "a trapezoid with a bottom base of $base1U, a top base of $base2U, and a height of $heightU";

              $area = ($base1+$base2)*$height/2;
              $ansA = NumberWithUnits("$area $unit^2");
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="YfP">
              Find the area of the trapezoid.
            </p>

            <sidebyside widths="40%" permid="uER">

              <image pg-name="$picture" permid="rhI">
                <description><var name="$alt" /></description>
              </image>

            </sidebyside>

            <p permid="EmY">
              Its area is <var name="$ansA" width="8" />.
            </p>

            <p permid="kuh">
              (Use <m>\text{cm}</m> for <var name="$unit" /> and
              <m>\text{cm}^2</m> for square <var name="$unit" />.)
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="wue">
            <p permid="ujs">
              A trapezoid's area can be calculated by this formula:
              <md permid="AWT">
                <mrow>\text{trapezoid area}\amp= \frac{1}{2}(\text{base1}+\text{base2})cdot\text{height}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{2}(<var name="$base1U" />+<var name="$base2U" />)(<var name="$heightU" />)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = <var name="$ansA" /></mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="acg">
    <title>Circle</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-circle" permid="foP">
      <caption>Circle</caption>
      <image width="60%" permid="uco">
        <description>a circle is shown with a radius from the center to the edge of 3 cm;the diameter of 6cm is also shown</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[fill=blue!20!white] (0,0) circle [radius=3];
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray,very thin] (-4,-4) grid (4,4);
                        \draw [red] (0,0) -- (3,0);
                        \node at (1.5,0) [above, red] {radius=$3$ cm};
                        \draw [brown] (1,2.83) -- (-1,-2.83);
                        \node at (0.5,1.5) [left, brown] {diameter=$6$ cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="EWS">
      A circle's diameter is always twice the length of its radius.
      A circle's perimeter is called <term>circumference</term>.
          <idx><h>circumference</h></idx>
      Deriving a circle's circumference and area formulas will be discussed in later math classes.
      For now, we will simply learn how to use them:
      <dl permid="lUZ">
        <li permid="nKm">
          <title>Circle's Circumference</title>
          <p permid="YBo">
            <m>C=\pi d=2\pi r</m>,
            where <m>C</m> stands for a circle's circumference,
            <m>d</m> for diameter, and <m>r</m> for radius.
              <idx><h>perimeter</h><h>circle</h></idx>
              <idx><h>circumference</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="TRv">
          <title>Circle's Area</title>
          <p permid="EIx">
            <m>A=\pi r^2</m>,
            where <m>A</m> stands for a circle's area, and <m>r</m> for radius.
              <idx><h>area</h><h>circle</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </p>

    <p permid="leb">
      The constant <m>\pi</m>'s value is <m>3.1415926\ldots</m>.
      A scientific calculator has a <m>\pi</m> button,
      so we don't have to type its value digit by digit.
    </p>

    <example permid="pUY">
      <statement>
        <p permid="WqC">
          A circle's diameter is <m>10</m> meters.
          Find the following values.

          <ol permid="tzy">
            <li permid="Sci">
              <p permid="kPG">
                Find the circle's circumference.
                Leave the result in terms of <m>\pi</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="yjr">
              <p permid="QWP">
                Find the circle's circumference.
                Round the result to two decimal places.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="eqA">
              <p permid="xdY">
                Find the circle's area.
                Leave the result in terms of <m>\pi</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="KxJ">
              <p permid="dlh">
                Find the circle's area.
                Round the result to two decimal places.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="rKl">
        <p permid="aqB">
          <ol permid="Nsp">
            <li permid="qES">
              <p permid="Jsq">
                We will use a circle's circumference formula:
                <md permid="hec">
                  <mrow>C\amp=\pi d</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\pi(10\text{ m})</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=10\pi\text{ m}</mrow>
                </md>
                The circle's circumference is <m>10\pi</m> meters.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="WMb">
              <p permid="pzz">
                We will use a circle's circumference formula:
                <md permid="Nll">
                  <mrow>C\amp=\pi d</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=(3.1415926\ldots)(10\text{ m})</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\approx31.42\text{ m}</mrow>
                </md>
                The circle's circumference is approximately <m>31.42</m> meters.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="CTk">
              <p permid="VGI">
                To find a circle's area,
                we need to find its radius, which is half of its diameter.
                Since its diameter is <m>10</m> meters,
                its radius is <m>5</m> meters.
                We will use a circle's area formula:
                <md permid="tsu">
                  <mrow>A\amp=\pi r^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\pi(5\text{ m})^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=25\pi\text{ m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                The circle's area is <m>25\pi</m> square meters.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="jat">
              <p permid="BNR">
                We will use a circle's area formula:
                <md permid="ZzD">
                  <mrow>A\amp=\pi r^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=(3.1415926\ldots)(5\text{ m})^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp\approx78.54\text{ m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                The circle's area is <m>78.54</m> square meters.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="fvT">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Geometry/CircleCircumferenceArea20.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="Gjp">
    <title>Perimeter and Area of Other Shapes</title>
    <p permid="Rlk">
      In many situations,
      we have to handle shapes consisting of various basic shapes we saw earlier.
      We will learn how to find perimeter and area of such shapes.
    </p>

    <example permid="Wch">
      <statement>
        <p permid="CxL">
          Find the perimeter and area of the following shape.
        </p>

        <figure permid="iEU">
          <caption>A Rectangle with a Missing Piece</caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="ajx">
            <description>a shape made from a 10 ft wide by 6 ft high rectangle with the upper left corner cut out;the base is 10 ft, the right side is 6 ft high, the top width is 7 ft, the side with the cutout is 4 ft high. The remaining two sides are unlabeled</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.6cm,y=0.6cm]
                        \draw[fill=blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (10,0) -- (10,6) -- (3,6) -- (3,2) -- (0,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,0.4) -- (0.4,0.4) -- (0.4,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,1.6) -- (0.4,1.6) -- (0.4,2);
                        \draw [red] (3,2.4) -- (2.6,2.4) -- (2.6,2);
                        \draw [red] (3.4,6) -- (3.4,5.6) -- (3,5.6);
                        \draw [red] (10,5.6) -- (9.6,5.6) -- (9.6,6);
                        \draw [red] (10,0.4) -- (9.6,0.4) -- (9.6,0);
                        \node at (5,0) [below] {$10$ ft};
                        \node at (6.5,6) [above] {$7$ ft};
                        \node at (3,4) [right] {$4$ ft};
                        \node at (10,3) [right] {$6$ ft};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="XRu">
        <p permid="GxK">
          To find this shape's perimeter,
          we must find the missing length of those two segments.
          We can do that simply by subtraction:
        </p>

        <figure permid="LhD">
          <caption>Calculating Lengths of Missing Segments</caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="GqG">
            <description>the previous shape with calculations for the two missing sides;to find the left side remaining after the cutout subtract 6-4=2;to find the top side remaining after the cutout subtract 10-7=3</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.6cm,y=0.6cm]
                        \draw[fill=blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (10,0) -- (10,6) -- (3,6) -- (3,2) -- (0,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,0.4) -- (0.4,0.4) -- (0.4,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,1.6) -- (0.4,1.6) -- (0.4,2);
                        \draw [red] (3,2.4) -- (2.6,2.4) -- (2.6,2);
                        \draw [red] (3.4,6) -- (3.4,5.6) -- (3,5.6);
                        \draw [red] (10,5.6) -- (9.6,5.6) -- (9.6,6);
                        \draw [red] (10,0.4) -- (9.6,0.4) -- (9.6,0);
                        \node at (5,0) [below] {$10$ ft};
                        \node at (6.5,6) [above] {$7$ ft};
                        \node at (3,4) [right] {$4$ ft};
                        \node at (10,3) [right] {$6$ ft};
                        \node [red] at (1,2) [above] {$10-7=3$ ft};
                        \node [red] at (0,1) [left] {$6-4=2$ ft};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p permid="mET">
          Now we can calculate the perimeter.
          We will start from the top right corner,
          walking down and around the shape while adding up the distance traveled:
          <me permid="FGM">
            \text{perimeter}=6\text{ ft}+10\text{ ft}+2\text{ ft}+3\text{ ft}+4\text{ ft}+7\text{ ft}=32\text{ ft}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p permid="SMc">
          There are two methods to calculate this shape's area.
          Let's look at the next figure:
        </p>

        <figure permid="roM">
          <caption>Calculating the Shape's Area</caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="mxP">
            <description>the previous shape is divided into two rectangles;along the bottom there is a 10 ft by 4 ft rectangle;sitting on top to the right is a 4 ft by 7 ft rectangle;a second way to calculate the area is shown with the larger 10 ft by 6 ft rectangle and the cutout which is 4 ft by 3 ft</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.6cm,y=0.6cm]
                        \draw[fill=blue!20!white] (0,0) -- (10,0) -- (10,6) -- (3,6) -- (3,2) -- (0,2) -- (0,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,0.4) -- (0.4,0.4) -- (0.4,0);
                        \draw [red] (0,1.6) -- (0.4,1.6) -- (0.4,2);
                        \draw [red] (3,2.4) -- (2.6,2.4) -- (2.6,2);
                        \draw [red] (3.4,6) -- (3.4,5.6) -- (3,5.6);
                        \draw [red] (10,5.6) -- (9.6,5.6) -- (9.6,6);
                        \draw [red] (10,0.4) -- (9.6,0.4) -- (9.6,0);
                        \node at (5,0) [below] {$10$ ft};
                        \node at (6.5,6) [above] {$7$ ft};
                        \node at (3,4) [right] {$4$ ft};
                        \node at (10,3) [right] {$6$ ft};
                        \node at (1.5,2) [above] {$3$ ft};
                        \node at (0,1) [left] {$2$ ft};
                        \draw [red,dashed] (3,2) -- (10,2);
                        \draw [red,dashed] (0,2) -- (0,6) -- (3,6);
                        \node at (5,1) [red] {($10\text{ ft})\cdot(2\text{ ft})=20\text{ ft}^2$};
                        \node at (6.5,4) [red] {($7\text{ ft})\cdot(4\text{ ft})=28\text{ ft}^2$};
                        \node at (1.5,4.3) [red] {$(3\text{ ft})\cdot(4\text{ ft})$};
                        \node at (1.5,3.8) [red] {$=12\text{ ft}^2$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p permid="yTl">
          The first method is to add up those two blue rectangle's area:
          <me permid="lNV">
            \text{area}=20\text{ ft}^2+28\text{ ft}^2=48\text{ ft}^2
          </me>
        </p>

        <p permid="fau">
          The second method is to calculate the big
          <m>10\times6</m> rectangle's area (<m>60\text{ ft}^2</m>),
          and then subtract the missing rectangle's area:
          <me permid="RVe">
            \text{area}=60\text{ ft}^2-12\text{ ft}^2=48\text{ ft}^2
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="LDc">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Geometry/RectanglePerimeterArea50.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </section>

  <section permid="mqy">
    <title>Volume</title>
    <p permid="xst">
      <term>Volume</term>
          <idx><h>volume</h></idx>
      is the quantity of three-dimensional space enclosed by a closed surface.
      We measure area by unit squares;
      similarly, we measure volume by unit cubes.
      Let's look at the following figure:
    </p>

    <figure permid="LvY">
      <caption>Volume of a Rectangular Prism</caption>
      <image width="47%" permid="SEY">
        <description>a rectangular box made of 1 inch cubes;it is 5 cubes wide, 4 cubes deep and 3 cubes high</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                \newcommand{\drawbox}[4]{
                \pgfmathsetmacro \angle {30}
                \pgfmathsetmacro \xd {{2/3*cos(\angle)}}
                \pgfmathsetmacro \yd {{2/3*sin(\angle)}}
                \pgfmathsetmacro \x {{#1-1+(#2-1)*(\xd)}}
                \pgfmathsetmacro \y {{#3-1+(#2-1)*(\yd)}}

                \draw[fill=#4] (\x,\y) -- (\x+1,\y) -- (\x+1,\y+1) -- (\x,\y+1) -- cycle;
                \draw[fill=#4] (\x,\y+1) -- (\x+\xd,\y+1+\yd) -- (\x+1+\xd,\y+1+\yd) -- (\x+1,\y+1) -- cycle;
                \draw[fill=#4] (\x+1,\y+1) -- (\x+1+\xd,\y+1+\yd) -- (\x+1+\xd,\y+\yd) -- (\x+1,\y) -- cycle;
                }
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \drawbox{1}{4}{1}{white}\drawbox{1}{3}{1}{white}\drawbox{1}{2}{1}{white}\drawbox{1}{1}{1}{white}
                    \drawbox{2}{4}{1}{white}\drawbox{2}{3}{1}{white}\drawbox{2}{2}{1}{white}\drawbox{2}{1}{1}{white}
                    \drawbox{3}{4}{1}{white}\drawbox{3}{3}{1}{white}\drawbox{3}{2}{1}{white}\drawbox{3}{1}{1}{white}
                    \drawbox{4}{4}{1}{white}\drawbox{4}{3}{1}{white}\drawbox{4}{2}{1}{white}\drawbox{4}{1}{1}{white}
                    \drawbox{5}{4}{1}{white}\drawbox{5}{3}{1}{white}\drawbox{5}{2}{1}{white}\drawbox{5}{1}{1}{white}
                    \drawbox{1}{4}{2}{white}\drawbox{1}{3}{2}{white}\drawbox{1}{2}{2}{white}\drawbox{1}{1}{2}{white}
                    \drawbox{2}{4}{2}{white}\drawbox{2}{3}{2}{white}\drawbox{2}{2}{2}{white}\drawbox{2}{1}{2}{white}
                    \drawbox{3}{4}{2}{white}\drawbox{3}{3}{2}{white}\drawbox{3}{2}{2}{white}\drawbox{3}{1}{2}{white}
                    \drawbox{4}{4}{2}{white}\drawbox{4}{3}{2}{white}\drawbox{4}{2}{2}{white}\drawbox{4}{1}{2}{white}
                    \drawbox{5}{4}{2}{white}\drawbox{5}{3}{2}{white}\drawbox{5}{2}{2}{white}\drawbox{5}{1}{2}{white}
                    \drawbox{1}{4}{3}{white}\drawbox{1}{3}{3}{white}\drawbox{1}{2}{3}{white}\drawbox{1}{1}{3}{white}
                    \drawbox{2}{4}{3}{white}\drawbox{2}{3}{3}{white}\drawbox{2}{2}{3}{white}\drawbox{2}{1}{3}{white}
                    \drawbox{3}{4}{3}{white}\drawbox{3}{3}{3}{white}\drawbox{3}{2}{3}{white}\drawbox{3}{1}{3}{white}
                    \drawbox{4}{4}{3}{white}\drawbox{4}{3}{3}{white}\drawbox{4}{2}{3}{white}\drawbox{4}{1}{3}{white}
                    \drawbox{5}{4}{3}{white}\drawbox{5}{3}{3}{white}\drawbox{5}{2}{3}{white}\drawbox{5}{1}{3}{white}

                    \node at (2.5,0) [below] {$5$ in};
                    \node at (0,1.5) [left] {$3$ in};
                    \node at (7,0.5) {$4$ in};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="dzC">
      The 3D shape in the figure is called a rectangular prism.
      It is composed of <m>1\text{ in}\times1\text{ in}\times1\text{ in}</m> unit cubes,
      with each cube's volume being <m>1</m> cubic inch
      (or <m>\text{in}^3</m>).
      The shape's volume is the number of such unit cubes.
      The bottom layer has <m>4\cdot5=20</m> unit cubes.
      Since there are <m>3</m> layers,
      the shape has a total of <m>3\cdot20=60</m> unit cubes.
      In other words, the shape's volume is <m>60\text{ in}^3</m>.
    </p>

    <p permid="JGL">
      Let's look at the same prism without cutting it into unit cubes:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-rectangular-prism" permid="rDh">
      <caption>A Rectangular Prism</caption>
      <image width="47%" permid="yMh">
        <description>the same rectangular prism without the cubes drawn in;the prism is 5 inches wide, 4 inches deep and 3 inches high</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,3) -- (0,3) -- (0,0);
                        \draw (5,0) -- (7,2) -- (7,5) -- (5,3);
                        \draw (7,5) -- (2,5) -- (0,3);
                        \draw [dashed] (2,5) -- (2,2) -- (7,2);
                        \draw [dashed] (2,2) -- (0,0);
                        \node at (2.5,0) [below] {$5\text{ in}$};
                        \node at (6,1) [right] {$4\text{ in}$};
                        \node at (0,1.5) [left] {$3\text{ in}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p permid="pNU">
      Earlier, we found the number of unit cubes in the bottom layer by doing <m>4\cdot5=20</m>,
      and then multiply <m>20</m> by <m>3</m> because there are three layers.
      Note that the area of the prism's base can also be calculated by <m>4\cdot5=20</m>,
      so a prism's volume formula is
      <me permid="ycn">
        V=Bh
      </me>
          <idx><h>volume</h><h>prism</h></idx>
      where <m>V</m> stands for volume,
      <m>B</m> for base area, and <m>h</m> for height.
    </p>

    <p permid="VVd">
      Now we can use the formula to calculate the prism's volume in <xref ref="figure-rectangular-prism">Figure</xref>:
      <md permid="ejw">
        <mrow>V\amp=Bh</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=(4\text{ in})(5\text{ in})(3\text{ in})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=60\text{ in}^3</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p permid="Ccm">
      A cylinder is not a prism,
      but its volume can also be calculated by the same formula.
      Let's look at an example.
    </p>

    <example permid="Cjq">
      <idx><h>volume</h><h>cylinder</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="OMd">
          Find the volume of a cylinder which has a radius of <m>3</m> meters and a height of <m>10</m> meters.
          First, write your result in terms of <m>\pi</m>,
          and then round the result to two decimal places.
        </p>

        <figure permid="uTm">
          <caption>A Cylinder</caption>
          <image width="30%" permid="eTq">
            <description>the shape of a can or cylinder is shown;the radius of the top and bottom is 3 meters;the height is 10 meters</description>

            <latex-image>
               <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (0,0) ellipse (1.25 and 0.5);
                        \draw (-1.25,0) -- (-1.25,-3.5);
                        \draw (-1.25,-3.5) arc (180:360:1.25 and 0.5);
                        \draw [dashed] (-1.25,-3.5) arc (180:360:1.25 and -0.5);
                        \draw (1.25,-3.5) -- (1.25,0);
                        \draw [red,dashed] (0,0) -- (1.25,0);
                        \node at (0.6,0) [red,above] {$3$ m};
                        \node at (-1.25,-1.75) [red,left] {$10$ m};
                        \fill [gray,opacity=0.5] (-1.25,0) -- (-1.25,-3.5) arc (180:360:1.25 and 0.5) -- (1.25,0) arc (0:180:1.25 and -0.5);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
               ]]>
               </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="DYD">
        <p permid="XvV">
          We will use the formula <m>V=Bh</m>.
          The base area can be calculated by <m>A=\pi r^2</m>, so we have:
          <md permid="KqF">
            <mrow>V\amp=Bh</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\pi r^2 h</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\pi (3\text{ m})^2(10\text{ m})</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=90 \pi\text{ m}^3</mrow>
          </md>
          The cylinder's volume is <m>90 \pi</m> cubic meters.
        </p>

        <p permid="DDe">
          Next, we will use a calculator to calculate the decimal value:
          <md permid="qxO">
            <mrow>V\amp=90\pi\text{ m}^3</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=90(3.1415926\ldots)\text{ m}^3</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp\approx282.74\text{ m}^3</mrow>
          </md>
          The cylinder's volume is approximately <m>282.74</m> cubic meters.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p permid="ijv">
      When we solve application problems,
      it's good practice to quickly check whether our solution is reasonable.
      If not, we must have made a mistake somewhere.
      Let's look at an example.
    </p>

    <example permid="iqz">
      <statement>
        <p permid="bav">
          Bill is measuring a cylindrical bucket to calculate how much water it can hold.
          The bucket's diameter is <m>18</m> inches,
          and its height is <m>2</m> feet.
          If <m>1</m> cubic feet is the same as <m>7.48</m> gallons,
          how many gallons of water can the bucket hold?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="kfM">
        <p permid="jKn">
          First, we will intentionally make a mistake.
          Since the diameter is <m>18</m> inches,
          the radius is <m>9</m> inches.
          We will use a cylinder's volume formula:
          <md permid="CMg">
            <mrow>V\amp=\pi r^2h</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=(3.1415926\ldots)(9)^2(2)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp\approx508.94</mrow>
          </md>
          Next, we will convert <m>508.94</m> cubic feet to gallons:
          <me permid="WEX">
            508.94\cdot7.48\approx3807
          </me>
          The bucket can hold approximately <m>3807</m> gallons of water.
        </p>

        <p permid="PRw">
          If we check the answer with common sense,
          it's easy to see it's impossible for a normal-sized bucket to hold thousands of gallons of water.
          We must have made a mistake somewhere.
        </p>

        <p permid="vYF">
          It turned out we forgot to use units in our calculation.
          If we did, we would have seen:
          <me permid="iTp">
            (3.1415926\ldots)(9\text{ in})^2(2\text{ ft})
          </me>
          Calculation cannot be done if units are not the same.
          We should have converted <m>9</m> inches to feet first:
          <me permid="Pay">
            9\text{ in}\cdot\frac{1\text{ ft}}{12\text{ in}}=0.75\text{ ft}
          </me>
          Let's redo the calculation with units:
          <md permid="boQ">
            <mrow>V\amp=\pi r^2h</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=(3.1415926\ldots)(0.75\text{ ft})^2(2\text{ ft})</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp\approx3.53\text{ ft}^3</mrow>
          </md>
          Next, we will convert <m>3.53</m> cubic feet to gallons:
          <me permid="vhH">
            3.53\text{ ft}^3\cdot\frac{7.48\text{ gal}}{1\text{ ft}^3}\approx26.44\text{ gal}
          </me>
          The bucket can hold approximately <m>26.44</m> gallons of water.
          This result is more reasonable.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </section>

